{
  "texts": [
    "The Rician K-factor is defined as K = λ 2 /(2σ 2 s), such that λ 2 = K/(K + 1) and 2σ 2 s = 1/(K + 1).",
    "The unconditional BEP over the Rician fading channels can be derived from the constant channel case asP e = ∞ 0 P e (r)f R (r)dr.(14)Substituting ( 12) and ( 13) into (14), we obtainP e = ∞ 0 r 2σ 2 s I 0 rλ σ 2 s exp - r 2 + λ 2 2σ 2 s × 1 -F Z 2N γ(r) σ 2 w (1 + r 2 δ) + F Z 2N γ(r) σ 2 w (1 + r 2 αδ) dr.(15)After performing the change of variables x = r 2 /(2σ 2 s), so that r = 2σ 2 s x and dr = σ 2 s (2x)dx, the unconditional BEP becomesP e = 1 2 e -λ 2 /(2σ 2 s) [I 1 -I 2 + I 3],(16)whereI 1 = ∞ 0 e -x I 0 λ 2x σ 2 s dx,(17a)I 2 = ∞ 0 e -x I 0 λ 2x σ 2 s F Z 2N γ( 2σ 2 s x) σ 2 w (1 + 2σ 2 s xδ) dx, (17b)andI 3 = ∞ 0 e -x I 0 λ 2x σ 2 s F Z 2N γ( 2σ 2 s x) σ 2 w (1 + 2σ 2 s xαδ) dx.",
    "(17c)To simplify the calculation of I 1, I 2, and I 3, which is convoluted, we use the Gauss-Laguerre quadrature method [9].",
    "This technique enables numerical approximation of integral expressions, significantly reducing the computational cost of evaluation.",
    "Thus (17) can be rewritten asI 1 ≈ Na j=1 w j I 0 λ 2x j σ 2 s, (18a)I 2 ≈ Na j=1 w j I 0 λ 2x j σ 2 s F Z 2N γ( 2σ 2 s x j) σ 2 w (2σ 2 s x j δ + 1), (18b)andI 3 ≈ Na j=1 w j I 0 λ 2x j σ 2 s F Z 2N γ( 2σ 2 s x j) σ 2 w (2σ 2 s x j αδ + 1), (18c) where x j denotes the roots of the Laguerre polynomial L Na (x), w j are the corresponding weights, and N a denotes the order of the quadrature rule, i.e., the number of sampling points used to approximate the integral.1 2 3 4 5 6 10 -8 10 -6 10 -4 10 -2 10 0 BEP =2.02 ( =8) subopt =1.88 ( opt =2.88 ( =25) =2.34 ( =25)Exact BEP Eq."
